    <Finding ID="Design--1--1">
        <ItemID>CMP--4</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            The Wall Detection &amp; Avoidance component explicitly states that, under the static map assumption, contradictory sensor evidence will never change map entries once they are set to FREE/ABSENT or PRESENT/BLOCKED:
            - In &lt;Execution&gt; it updates walls from UNKNOWN to PRESENT/ABSENT based on consistent detections.
            - In &lt;Failures&gt; it says contradictory evidence remains flagged as sensor error and does not change the map.
            DAT--7 repeats that no transitions from established FREE/ABSENT to BLOCKED/PRESENT are applied within a mission.
            This contradicts LL--RELIAB--1.2.2, which requires that, after at least N consecutive readings indicating a wall where the map currently stores FREE or ABSENT, the software shall change the established wall or cell classification.
            LL--MAP--1.3.5 only forbids flipping between FREE/BLOCKED and PRESENT/ABSENT or reverting to UNKNOWN; it does not forbid FREE-&gt;BLOCKED or ABSENT-&gt;PRESENT transitions. The design misinterprets the static map requirement and violates the consistency-check requirement.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Update the static map and consistency-check design to allow:
            - CellState transitions: UNKNOWN -&gt; FREE, UNKNOWN -&gt; BLOCKED, and FREE -&gt; BLOCKED when LL--RELIAB--1.2.2 consistency criteria (N consecutive contradictory readings) are met.
            - WallState transitions: UNKNOWN -&gt; PRESENT, UNKNOWN -&gt; ABSENT, and ABSENT -&gt; PRESENT (and possibly PRESENT -&gt; ABSENT) when LL--RELIAB--1.2.2 criteria are met.
            Concretely:
            - Modify CMP--3 &lt;Execution&gt; and &lt;Invariants&gt; to permit these one-way “strengthening” transitions (FREE-&gt;BLOCKED, ABSENT-&gt;PRESENT) and state that changes from FREE to BLOCKED and from ABSENT to PRESENT are allowed but never reversed within a mission.
            - Modify CMP--4 &lt;Execution&gt; and &lt;Failures&gt; so that, after N consecutive contradictory readings, mapping updates are requested to change the classification rather than always treating them as mere sensor errors.
            - Update DAT--1 and DAT--7 to reflect the correct allowed transition set consistent with LL--MAP--1.3.5 and LL--RELIAB--1.2.2.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--2">
        <ItemID>DAT--1</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            DAT--1 (Cell and Wall Enumerations) defines allowed transitions only from UNKNOWN to FREE/BLOCKED and from WALL_UNKNOWN to PRESENT/ABSENT, and explicitly states:
            “No reverse transitions or cross transitions (FREE to BLOCKED, PRESENT to ABSENT, etc.) are permitted within a mission.”
            LL--MAP--1.3.5 constrains:
            (1) cells: may change only from UNKNOWN to FREE or UNKNOWN to BLOCKED and shall not revert to UNKNOWN;
            (2) walls: may change only from UNKNOWN to PRESENT or UNKNOWN to ABSENT and shall not change between PRESENT and ABSENT or revert to UNKNOWN.
            LL--RELIAB--1.2.2, however, explicitly requires the ability to change an established FREE or ABSENT classification when N consecutive contradictory readings are received. Under a strict reading of LL--MAP--1.3.5, “change between PRESENT and ABSENT” is forbidden but ABSENT-&gt;PRESENT may still be disallowed; however, FREE-&gt;BLOCKED is not prohibited. DAT--1’s blanket ban on FREE-&gt;BLOCKED and ABSENT-&gt;PRESENT makes it impossible to satisfy LL--RELIAB--1.2.2 for cells, and likely contradicts the intended interpretation for walls.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Relax and clarify the transition policy in DAT--1 to align with both LL--MAP--1.3.5 and LL--RELIAB--1.2.2:
            - For cells, explicitly allow:
                * UNKNOWN -&gt; FREE
                * UNKNOWN -&gt; BLOCKED
                * FREE -&gt; BLOCKED when N consecutive contradictory readings (LL--RELIAB--1.2.2) are observed.
              and forbid:
                * BLOCKED -&gt; FREE
                * any transition back to UNKNOWN.
            - For walls, define a one-way strengthening:
                * WALL_UNKNOWN -&gt; PRESENT or ABSENT as initial classification.
                * ABSENT -&gt; PRESENT (or PRESENT -&gt; ABSENT if required by requirements interpretation) when N consecutive contradictory readings accumulate, if LL--RELIAB--1.2.2 is interpreted to apply to walls as well.
              and forbid toggling back and forth or reverting to UNKNOWN.
            Update the prose in DAT--1 so it no longer contradicts LL--RELIAB--1.2.2 and is consistent with the corrected mapping behavior specified in CMP--3 and CMP--4.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--3">
        <ItemID>DAT--7</ItemID>
        <Severity>Major</Severity>
        <Description>
            DAT--7 describes parameter N for sensor data consistency checks and states:
            “Due to static map assumption, such transitions are not applied within a mission; instead, the detection is treated as sensor error, and the map remains unchanged...”
            LL--RELIAB--1.2.2 requires that, after at least N consecutive readings indicating a wall where the map currently stores FREE or ABSENT, the software shall change the established classification. Treating all such cases as sensor errors and never updating the map violates this requirement. This text reinforces the incorrect treatment already described in CMP--3 and CMP--4, effectively nullifying LL--RELIAB--1.2.2.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Redefine the role of N in DAT--7 to directly support LL--RELIAB--1.2.2:
            - Specify that if there are N consecutive contradictory readings indicating a wall where the map currently stores FREE or ABSENT (or similarly for PRESENT/ABSENT walls, if applicable), then:
                * For cells: change state FREE -&gt; BLOCKED.
                * For walls: change ABSENT -&gt; PRESENT (or PRESENT -&gt; ABSENT per chosen policy in line with LL--MAP--1.3.5’s intent).
            - Remove or rephrase the sentence stating that such transitions are not applied within a mission. Instead, say that after such a change, the new classification is treated as final and will not be reverted during the mission.
            - Align CMP--3 and CMP--4 behaviors with this updated definition so that LL--RELIAB--1.2.2 is concretely implemented rather than bypassed.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--4">
        <ItemID>DAT--2</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
            DAT--2 specifies:
            - horizontalWalls[5][8] for r = 0..4 and
            - verticalWalls[4][9] for c = 0..8.
            For a maze with 4 rows (0..3) and 8 columns (0..7), this implies:
            - 5 horizontal boundaries (0..4) is correct: above row 0, between rows 0-1, 1-2, 2-3, and below row 3.
            - 9 vertical boundaries (0..8) is also correct: left of col 0, between 0-1..6-7, and right of col 7.
            However, LL--ENV--1.4.1 requires that possible wall positions be stored as boundaries between horizontally and vertically adjacent cells. The indexing description includes boundaries outside the cell adjacency (outer perimeters), but the mapping of “between cell (r, c) and (r, c+1): verticalWalls[r][c+1]” and similarly for rows uses only internal boundaries. This is subtly correct but confusing: the indices at r=0 / r=4 and c=0 / c=8 represent outer maze borders, which are not explicitly described or constrained by the requirements.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
            Clarify DAT--2 by:
            - Explicitly distinguishing interior inter-cell walls (between adjacent cells) from outer boundary walls, e.g., noting that:
                * For adjacency between (r, c) and (r+1, c), only r in 0..2 and horizontalWalls[r+1][c] are used.
                * For adjacency between (r, c) and (r, c+1), only c in 0..6 and verticalWalls[r][c+1] are used.
            - Clearly documenting the semantics of the border indices (r=0, r=4, c=0, c=8), whether they represent fixed outer walls, map boundaries, or are unused/don’t-care.
            This makes the indexing scheme unambiguous and easier to implement correctly, without changing behavior.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>
</Findings>
